Transpose a square matrix.
The matrix can be any size, but is guaranteed to be square (width and height are the same).  Here is an example of a 3x3 matrix:  input:

0 1 2
3 4 5
6 7 8

transposed:

0 3 6
1 4 7
2 5 8  You represent matrices in c++ with a vector of vectors,  vector<vector<int> > .  Here is a function you can paste at the beginning of your program (after  using namespace std; ) that will allow you to print vectors using cout:  template <typename T>
ostream& operator<<(ostream& o, const vector<T>& v) {
    cout << '{';
    if (v.size() > 0) {
        for (unsigned i = 0; i < v.size() - 1; ++i) {
            o << v.at(i) << ", ";
        }
        o << v.at(v.size() - 1);
    }
    o << '}';
    return o;
}  Hint :
You do not need to transpose this matrix in-place.
